    question: 'What is the INPS contribution rate for employees in Italy?',
    answer: 'Private-sector employees pay <strong>9.19%</strong> of their gross salary as INPS social security contributions (contributi previdenziali). For salaries exceeding the first pension bracket (approximately &euro;55,000 per year in 2026), an additional 1% is charged on the excess portion. These contributions fund your future pension, unemployment insurance (NASpI), short-time work support (cassa integrazione), and sick/maternity pay. The employer also pays roughly 30% on top, but this is not deducted from your payslip.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Why does net salary vary between Italian regions?',
    answer: 'On top of national IRPEF, every Italian region and municipality levies its own surcharge (addizionale regionale and addizionale comunale). Regional rates range from 0.70% in Trentino-Alto Adige for low incomes up to 3.33% in Lazio for high incomes. Municipal surcharges vary from 0% to 0.9%. On a &euro;30,000 salary, the difference between the cheapest and most expensive region can exceed &euro;600 per year. You can use our <a href="/en/region-comparison/" class="text-brand hover:underline">region comparison tool</a> to see the exact figures.',
  },
  {
    question: 'How does the net salary calculation change with dependent family members?',
    answer: 'Since March 2022, the old <em>detrazioni per familiari a carico</em> (deductions for dependent family members) for children under 21 have been replaced by the <strong>Assegno Unico Universale</strong> (AUU), a direct monthly payment from <a href="https://www.inps.it/it/it/dettaglio-scheda.schede-servizio-strumento.schede-servizi.assegno-unico-universale-50699.assegno-unico-universale.html" class="text-brand hover:underline">INPS</a> that depends on your ISEE (household income indicator) and the number of children. This benefit is <strong>not</strong> shown on your payslip and does not affect the gross-to-net calculation. However, deductions for a <strong>dependent spouse</strong> and for children <strong>aged 21 and over</strong> who earn less than &euro;2,840.51/year (or &euro;4,000 if under 24) still apply and reduce your IRPEF. For a dependent spouse with taxable income of &euro;30,000, the deduction is approximately &euro;690/year, which increases your annual net by that same amount. These deductions are regulated by <a href="https://www.normattiva.it/uri-res/N2Ls?urn:nir:stato:decreto.presidente.repubblica:1986-12-22;917" class="text-brand hover:underline">Art. 12 of the TUIR (D.P.R. 917/1986)</a>.',
  },
  {
    question: 'What is the no-tax area (area di non tassazione) in Italy?',
    answer: 'The <strong>no-tax area</strong> refers to the income threshold below which an employee effectively pays zero IRPEF, thanks to the <em>detrazione per lavoro dipendente</em> (employment income deduction). For 2026, this threshold is <strong>&euro;8,500</strong> of annual taxable income. At this level, the employment deduction (&euro;1,955) fully offsets the gross IRPEF due (8,500 &times; 23% = &euro;1,955). An employee earning up to &euro;8,500 in taxable income therefore owes no IRPEF, although INPS contributions (9.19%) are still deducted. This means a worker with a RAL of approximately &euro;9,360 or less would fall in the no-tax area. The mechanism is defined in <a href="https://www.normattiva.it/uri-res/N2Ls?urn:nir:stato:decreto.presidente.repubblica:1986-12-22;917" class="text-brand hover:underline">Art. 13 of the TUIR</a> and confirmed by the <a href="https://www.agenziaentrate.gov.it/portale/web/guest/irpef" class="text-brand hover:underline">Agenzia delle Entrate</a>.',
  },
];
